##"middle-aged people have nowhere to cry in epidemic areas" | 510 calls from Wuhan psychological consultant

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

A 2004 survey by the Peking University Institute of Mental Health found that 16.4% and 10.1% of discharged SARS patients had depression and anxiety within three months. The infectious disease has been linked to a range of mental illnesses, with the incidence of mental disorders following major disasters ranging from 10% to 20% , according to national and International Studies, common symptoms include: post-traumatic Stress Reaction, depression, anxiety, somatization reaction and so on.

Similar to SARS, the new type of pneumonia also has the characteristics of sudden occurrence, strong infectivity and lack of specific therapeutic drugs. Forced isolation, closed living environment, and highly stimulating information updating bring different degrees of psychological damage to different groups of people. It may invade medical staff, patients and their families, as well as healthy people.

After the outbreak, various provinces and cities have set up their own psychological assistance hotline. Professor Xiao Jingsong, president of Hubei Association of Psychological Counselors, set up the Hubei Psychological Hotline (15342296955) the day Wuhan announced the closure of the city. She became one of the first psychologists on the Hubei Heart Association hotline.

Du, who trained in psychology for many years, obtained a certificate as a psychological consultant in 2013. In 2014, she was diagnosed with breast cancer and began using psychology to support her treatment and rehabilitation. In the Cancer Center of Union Hospital affiliated to Tongji Medical College, we have accumulated a large number of cases and experiences of tumor psychological crisis intervention and mental health counseling.

From January 23 to February 5, the team of the Hubei psychological hotline received 510 calls for help, providing more than 1,000 psychological crisis interventions. Ninety-five percent of them were from non-medical sources. Some take their temperature every 30 minutes, others seal themselves in a room because they're suspicious... the damage from a new crown is not only physical, it's also a shock to the heart.

After the outbreak, Du worked until the wee hours of the morning, often in a state of deep exhaustion, but she always answered questions in a gentle, calm tone. She had heard different cries and tribulations, and sometimes she would follow the people on the other end of the phone in tears, slowly soothing each other, gently rubbing the folds of their hearts.

At the end of the interview on February 7, she choked up and said, "there's so little we can do. I really hope that through my little voice, I can call on all of us to make a difference and cherish that little bit of health more. " A little freedom. "

The following is his account.

The following is his account.

By Lin Qiuming

Editor | Xiao Zhu

1

Dr. Li Wenliang passed away. This event is a point through which we can see the whole pain.

Between the outbreak and February 5, our hotline received 510 calls.

When health care workers call, the most common signs are lassitude and powerlessness about the epidemic, as well as anxiety and fear about their situation.

I received a call from a smoking doctor who had worked nine hours straight, working hard, and had to take valium at night to fall asleep.

She has to face a lot of fever patients every day, some patients, she needs to ear close to their mouth, droplets are difficult to guard against. The goggles were so fogged, I couldn't write the chart, so I had to take them off. All the details of the job made her very anxious.

Some of the psychological problems that doctors may experience, such as depression and relationship sensitivity, can only be assessed in anticipation, a warning based on past experience. From an early age, we connected to the nursing departments of the major hospitals in Wuhan. Larger hospitals have set up their own psychological hotline, they also have internal psychological support system, we encountered the situation of the first-line medical staff, most of the current is relatively stable.

In fact, less than 5% of the staff we serve don't have time to make calls. Compared to the rest of the population, their state of mind will lag a bit, perhaps until the epidemic is almost over, they may have the energy to take care of their state of mind.

It won't be too late to intervene. All individuals will have a bottom line and management, there are psychological self-repair mechanisms, do not have to rely on external forces, they can complete.

I think most health care workers are going to survive this, and this is just one of the things that happens in their careers. Some of the medical staff called US and said they were scared and couldn't even stand it, but the words were instantaneous, and everyone had them. It was an expression, not an attitude. After they finished crying and talking, they went to work the next day with great perseverance. We can not judge his whole state out of context according to his present situation.

This is the professional quality of a medical staff, we can not despise their self-repair ability, do not deliberately find them break the moment, in fact, these moments are very few. More often than not, they demand that they do their jobs as usual and stronger than ever, and they deserve our respect.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Dr. Rao Xin of Zhongnan Hospital, Wuhan University, injured one leg and still walking with a cane

2

At first, 90% of the people asking for help were women, who were better communicators and better at asking for help than men, who were more likely to hide themselves, especially when it came to expressing vulnerable parts of themselves. Now the numbers are changing, and the number of men is slowly increasing, approaching the 7 to 3 ratio, and the focus is becoming more and more the same, it's a matter of life and death, there's no clear cut line.

A young man called in in a very depressed state, his mother-in-law and wife have been in the hospital, his own diagnosis of a mild infection.

Instead of day-to-day counseling, we are now a crisis intervention. The intervention is graded, and the first level is an online intervention that can be done in about 10 minutes, during which the counselor will assess the other person's status and make an online assessment. If 10 minutes of confirmation is not enough, we will have further support. The second level is according to his condition, will transfer to the backstage, lets the psychological consultant call back again to go over. There is also a level 3 situation where we engage the community for more practical help when his problems and status require continuous follow up.

With this young man, after our therapist gave him a level one intervention online, his condition stabilized and he was able to watch TV at home alone. We went ahead and sent the news to the media and the community, and the community confirmed it to us, and when they found out it was true, they immediately arranged for a person and a car, and a hospital bed for this patient with a mild infection.

In addition to doctors, patients, the families of infected people are also susceptible to the epidemic. They are with the patients all the time, because the families of the people who died in this epidemic, they will be more serious.

One morning, a woman called to say that her parents were ill and in two different hospitals, and that she had to travel twice a day to buy breakfast for her father, and to go to another hospital to be with her mother. She was afraid that if she ever came back, dad would be gone. She was an only child, and now she can't get a nurse, and the stress and panic made her cry on the phone.

I told her to eat and get her mind right. When she calmed down, I referred her to another counselor for a three-level follow-up.

We sometimes shed tears with the person on the other end of the line, as a sign of compassion and empathy, as well as the therapist's perception of him. In this state, the counselor is the same frequency with her, the psychologist has a dual identity, I flow is her tears.

We have more than 20 counsellors in primary intervention and 202 in secondary intervention. We request to do a level of answering the consulting teacher, consulting time to have more than 200 hours, age in 40 years old or so, need to have rich experience. Consultants are on a rotating schedule, and they're not too busy at the moment. The manpower is adequate, even unsaturated, and we want more people to be able to find us.

Wuhan and other counties and cities in Hubei Province accounted for two thirds of the calls received, with a third coming from across the country. Two days ago, a Jiangsu consultant called to say, I just take a second, I came to thank you, I am much better now. Heilongjiang in the north, Hainan in the south. We've all gotten calls. After the fight, they will say, sorry, we have occupied your Hubei Resources, thank you for your support. It's very moving.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A Southwest Medical University Hospital is offering a long distance video therapy to a medical team in Hubei Province

3

A very important psychological trend in the current situation is the increase in the number of "doubters" (who suspect they have won a new title) . Some people think they're sick, and they put themselves in isolation. When he is in a single space, loneliness, fear and anxiety will peak. I am very touched by the kind of people who call in. It is a choice based on love and responsibility, and I would rather bear the consequences on my own, than to bother my family.

There's also a story about love and responsibility. The youngest counselor we've ever had was 12 years old. As soon as I answered the phone, I heard a scolding voice beside me. His mother said, "don't fight, you must fight. ". The kid's yelling at his mom, "mom, I'm calling for you. ". Mom didn't say a word. He turned to me and said, my mother is so anxious. I said yes, you need us to give you what support, he thought to tell me, send me an expert.

Kids just want to help their moms. He was later put on speakerphone, and the whole family gathered to chat, relieved. His mother's condition is more serious, and it's a common anxiety, and we all have it. At this time to adjust their mentality, do some other things, the length of the outbreak of psychological expectations. Some people will be constantly forced to refresh the news, it can be understood as their sense of responsibility and attention to major events, but do not because refresh their emotions, to control the degree.

The age group that comes for help now is two-thirds higher in the middle, between the ages of 30 and 50.

Those in the Middle Age group have more to bear. They are the main source of family income, at this time the balance of payments is broken, there will certainly be some pressure. But now that the needs are at the bottom, the stress of life itself is at the top, and everyone has been pushed back to the point of origin by the epidemic.

Middle-aged people often express the conflict between their responsibilities and the epidemic. He secretly knows what he has to give. They have nowhere to cry. He feels that he can not reveal his real fear and inner self in front of his family. Many people waited until the last minute to call, and our teacher told him that you could cry. That's when he cries on the phone.

We will listen and respond, and when he has settled down, give him professional support, do some analysis of the situation, and finally give him encouragement and affirmation, emphasizing his sense of responsibility. Feel the inspiration of this belief, will support him a little longer. It's all part of the process. Listening, responding, and clarifying are the first three steps of our intervention, followed by assessment and judgment.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image source visual China

Clarification means clarifying whether they are in an emotional state or a physical state. There is basically no order or logic to what a person is saying in an emotional state, and we need to explain why he or she is there.

One Guy told us that he took his temperature several times a day, every half hour, around 36 or 37 degrees, and I said to him, look at the temperature you've taken several times, and it's currently below 37 degrees, right? These are normal. Only after hearing this confirmation did he come to his senses.

What people are generally looking for help with is sleep improvement. Unable to sleep, the first thing to do is to confirm that the cause of the inability to sleep is psychological or physiological reasons, is the cause of their own disease or epidemic, and then to provide support accordingly.

A few days ago, we got a call from an old man who couldn't sleep. The Counselor Online taught him to do a progressive muscle relaxation, and the next day he called the hotline and said, you told me yesterday (muscle relaxation) so I sleep very well, you tell me again, so I can sleep again.

He is a 60-year-old man in Wuhan. He lives at home with his wife. He has just had heart surgery. He can not go out on his own, and because the epidemic has been closed for more than 10 days, so he has not been downstairs for a month, i was so anxious, I couldn't sleep for six days.

When we did, we sent him the progressive muscle relaxation speech. After receiving it, he said, thank you so much. It may be a small thing for you, but it's too important for me. This is a little out of our jurisdiction, and we usually suggest that he download it himself. But the old man told us he couldn't surf the Internet, so we taught him step by step.

In addition to taking your temperature and not being able to sleep, many people at home also have poor appetite. I called my local relatives in Wuhan and they all switched to eating twice a day, which is very common. In fact, this is a good phenomenon, we are adapting to change, the body and the rhythm of life are adapting to the current state of isolation. When the body doesn't exercise and burn as much, food naturally has to be reduced, so don't take it too seriously.

In recent days, there have been fewer healthy requests for help. People who already have mental health problems, such as depression and anxiety, start asking for help more often. Some patients have been medicated before, but the body remembers these feelings and Traumas, and these underlying diseases are reconnected and activated when important events related to the epidemic occur. They have also become a vulnerable group and deserve attention.

So far, our platform hasn't received a suicide threat, but we have received requests for help from other platforms.

One of my friends forwarded me a message from a girl who was anxious enough to think about suicide. We called, and the girl said, it's okay, it's okay. She was probably with her family, so she hung up the phone quickly. The extreme emotion of suicide was temporary. When she got the call, why did she say enough, because she knew what she was doing, that she had the attention of a stranger, and that she was satisfied with that attention.

A sentence of psychological assistance, perhaps 10 minutes, may change the fate of a person and a family. There will also be a number of people who can not be reached by hotlines, which will require greater publicity and assistance from the media and the government in order to provide timely support to those with psychological needs. But don't rely too much on psychological support, there are other ways to do this as well. There's a million ways to get home.

When it comes to psychological support, be Seek truth from facts, and don't overstate the usefulness of this hotline, I often tell our partners, there's not much we can do, there's only so much we can do. It's more important to know what we can't do than what we can do. Know this, and you won't feel powerless.

4

On the evening of the 6th, when we learned of Dr. Li Wenliang's condition, we compiled and sent out a picture and text. The key word was to survive, because for infected people, to survive is already a luxury.

Compared to previous crisis interventions, this one is happening fast, and everything is moving too fast. At the same time, it is a wide range of social effects of the spread of deeper.

The difficulty of assistance is not really in the minds of the psychological workers. If the early warning of the epidemic itself is timely and the event itself can have a good support and development, most people can adjust their mood quickly, the number of people who need help shrinks to a fraction of the number of people who don't need it.

Some high-risk cases, such as resentment toward doctors and people in Wuhan, are not just psychological problems. The front end of this thing is not the mind, but the thing itself, and back to the front end of the event. For the individual, conflict, despair and contradiction, from the former far end to his eyes, the balance is disturbed.

We got a call like that. It's hard to deal with that kind of resentment. All you can do is comfort, understanding, and compassion. Psychological support can only play a role of pacification, stable individual stage of psychological changes, but the effect will not last long, we can not predict which once again the balance was broken.

This individual can not bear the pain, can not be inspired by another life, or by the psychological counseling relationship to promote him to put down. It's going to take a lot more power, and there's a lot bigger social issues behind it.

In fact, for different groups of people, we end up in the direction of acceptance.

All of us must come to terms with what happened and what it will do to each individual, to each family and to society. For some young people, it was a moment when he understood what freedom was, what health was, what family was. To find out what impact and significance this event had on each of them. We all feel pain, but in the face of so much life's pain, there's something we can do to make it better.

When you called me, I was shopping at the supermarket. Before going to the supermarket, my sister and I sent something to my parents. We left our stuff at the door, they took it in, and we went downstairs, and we didn't talk much. When I went to the supermarket and saw the state of everyone around me, I suddenly felt very sad. At that moment, I stood there in tears.

I saw them covered up, heavily armed, doing every kind of protection imaginable. For example, if you put a shoe over your shoe, some people put on a disposable apron that eats hot pot. All the people who go to the supermarket to buy supplies for their daily lives are taking what they can carry and moving it home, whether it's young people or middle-aged or old people, because you can't drive, you have to carry it all the way by hand.

I felt so sad, how did it all come to this, that all my life had changed. The Gate of the community was sealed with barbed wire, only one door in and out of the body temperature, do registration. You're even grateful that the neighborhood grocery store is open, but you still have to Hoo Hoo Hoo, you have to shout at him what you want, and he hands it to you.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As a result of 3 cases diagnosed, a small area of Hubei is closed off, residents buy vegetables through iron gate picture source pear video

It's so different from before. Everyone on the street saw someone coming from the other side and walked away, not wanting to walk in the same air as each other. It's GonNa hurt. It's GonNa hurt. I also know that we all pay a price.

The death of Dr. Li Wenliang reflects a collective disappointment. It is not within the power of any individual to reconcile the emotional state of a group. A voice must be heard to restore balance and treat him fairly and fairly.

I hope that on June 6th, as a starting point, there will be a relatively fair and just voice to face life, to face all the people in the midst of the epidemic. Then perhaps from this day on, the psychological state of our society as a whole will go in a good direction, it is likely to become an inflection point.

Today (February 7) I told all my partners that we would not do interviews and would be silent for a day. For so many lives in reality, Dr. Lee is only one of the representatives. (sobs)

Recently Wuhan has been a cloudy day, the city is as stable as no one, only the occasional sound of birds. But it's not the day for the sun, it's the day for the snow.

Haven't you seen enough?
